Biomes

Organisms on Earth have adapted to the cyclic pattern of climate. Take as example deciduous plants; they thrive in spring to reproduce and loose their foliage in the fall to conserve energy in the harsh winter. Next year, they do the same. This is known as phenology, the cyclic and seasonal phenomena in nature. As a result, we find entire geographic regions inhabited by communities of organisms with similar adaptations. We call these regions biomes.

The main objectives for today are to:

  • Identify biomes given their climate diagrams
  • Explore why biomes are being reconsidered in the anthropocene (anthropogenic biomes)

Part I: Terrestrial biomes and climate diagrams


Step 1: Identify a terrestrial biome given its climate diagram

To visualize the patterns of temperature and precipitation that are associated with particular biomes, we can use climate diagrams. Since climate is the primary abiotic force shaping plant forms in different terrestrial biomes, you can expect locations around the world that are from a particular biome to have similar climate diagrams.

Part II: Biomes and climate change


Step 1: Explore the annual variation in temperature of coral reefs

In contrast to terrestrial biomes which are dominated by plants as primary producers, aquatic biomes are categorized by flow, depth and salinity. Take for instance coral reefs. Given the corals dependency on solar radiation for photosynthesis and their limited tolerance to seasonal changes in water temperature, this biome is constrained to shallow waters between 30N and 30S. However, several decades of climate change has put this biome - the second most diverse on Earth - under threat, opening questions into the boundaries of current biomes.

Go ahead, import puertorico to RStudio and explore the temperature data from coral reefs of Puerto Rico.

Plot the average temperature across months of one normal year (2004) and one warm year (2005). To get a summary of descriptive statistics (mean, SD, SE, 95%CI), use the function summarySE() in package Rmisc. The first argument in this function is the dataframe (puertorico), and the subsequent arguments are the column name of the variable to be summarized (dependent variable) and the column name containing the grouping variable (independent variable).

# Loading package tidyverse to filter data
library(tidyverse)

# Filtering data from 2004 and 2005
pr04 <- filter(puertorico,BYYY==2004)
pr05 <- filter(puertorico,BYYY==2005)

# Check the newly created dataframes
pr04
pr05

# Loading package Rmisc to estimate average temperature (SST) across months (BM) in 2004 and 2005
library(Rmisc)
sum04 <- summarySE(pr04,"SST","BM")
sum05 <- summarySE(pr05,"SST","BM")

# Plotting the average temperature (SST) across months (BM) in 2004 and 2005
library(ggplot2)
p1 <- ggplot(sum04,aes(BM,SST)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylim(24,30) +
  theme_classic()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1,12,1)) +
  xlab("Month")
p1

p2 <- ggplot(sum05,aes(BM,SST)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylim(24,30) +
  theme_classic()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1,12,1)) +
  xlab("Month")
p2



Question 1: Can you observe any difference in mean monthly temperature between both years? Explain.

Question 2: If the historical mean monthly maximum for this region is 28.5C and the bleaching threshold is 29.5C, how many weeks of thermal stress these corals experienced in 2005 versus 2004 (approximately)?

Coral bleaching is the loss of color a coral experiences after expelling their symbiotic algae. Coral bleaching occurs when corals experience stress due to higher than average temperatures. If coral bleaching takes place for prolong periods of time (weeks) corals are likely to die from starvation due to the absence of food from the algaes photosynthesis.
